<h2><b>BASIC ADDITION AND SUBSTRACTION </b></h2><br>

<p><b>Basic Addition:</b><br>
<b> Definition:</b><br>

Addition is a fundamental arithmetic operation that combines two or more numbers to find their total or sum.<br>
<b>Notation:</b><br>

The plus sign (+) is used to denote addition.<br>
Examples:<br>

5<br>
+<br>
3<br>
=<br>
8<br>
5+3=8<br>
12<br>
+<br>
7<br>
=<br>
19<br>
12+7=19<br>
2<br>
+<br>
9<br>
=<br>
11<br>
2+9=11<br>
Key Concepts:<br>

The order of numbers does not affect the sum: <br>
a<br>
+<br>
b<br>
=<br>
b<br>
+<br>
a<br>
a+b=b+a.<br>
Adding zero to any number gives the number itself: <br>
a<br>
+<br>
0<br>
=<br>
a<br>
a+0=a.<br>
<b>Basic Subtraction:</b><br>
<b>Definition:</b><br>

Subtraction is the arithmetic operation of finding the difference between two numbers.<br>
<b>Notation:</b><br>

The minus sign (-) is used to denote subtraction.<br>
Examples:<br>

8<br>
-<br>
3<br>
=<br>
5<br>
8-3=5<br>
15<br>
-<br>
6<br>
=<br>
9<br>
15-6=9<br>
10<br>
-<br>
4<br>
=<br>
6<br>
10-4=6<br>
Key Concepts:<br>

The order of subtraction matters: <br>
a<br>
-<br>
b<br>
a-b is not necessarily equal to <br>
b<br>
-<br>
a<br>
b-a.<br>
Subtracting zero from any number gives the number itself: <br>
a<br>
-<br>
0<br>
=<br>
a<br>
a-0=a<br>
<b>Additional Tips:</b><br>
<b>Number Line:</b> Visualizing addition as moving to the right on a number line and subtraction as moving to the left can be helpful.<br>

<b>Counting and Objects:</b> For beginners, counting objects (like candies or toys) can aid in understanding addition, while removing objects simulates subtraction.<br>

<b>Real-world Applications:</b> Understanding the practical uses of addition and subtraction, such as counting money or measuring ingredients for a recipe, can make these concepts more tangible.<br>

These basics serve as a foundation for more advanced mathematical concepts and problem-solving. If you have any specific questions or if you'd like more information, feel free to ask!<br>
</p><br>
